Finally, I get to place the little white cup on the rack. I press the button that says ‚Äúmocha.‚Äù The machine sputters, and the plastic nozzle protrudes toward my cup like a mosquito's proboscis. Creamy, delectable brown liquid flows gently into the cup. It is time. 

More words are said. Incoherent. Incoherent. More dishes clink. Clink clink. The mass of bodies sitting at tables, standing and talking, wading around the room, all continue to move in a pseudo-choreographed manner. 

I take the sip! 

‚ÄúAh-ha!‚Äù 

I am back.

I spin around. I say, ‚ÄúGood morning, friend.‚Äù

‚ÄúGood morning.‚Äù 

It wasn‚Äôt Chinese, after all. I can‚Äôt distinguish language in the post-caffeine mental dystopia. 

Maybe that is a problem.

@undefined here is my go at the prompt: 

I don't notice people; I do not even notice a lobby. I move quickly past them and head directly to the espresso machine. I do not notice the food either, but it is piping hot, and the people I did not notice are chewing and swallowing it in a frenzy. Fellow network schoolers? I recognize the scent of mocha, and the smell begins titillating my taste buds. Moving from my room to elevator to floor took forever, like slouching slowly toward Bethlehem. All that matters now is the dopamine hit to sate the reward circuitry. I need the jolt. Since waking up, my brain has cried out, ‚Äúcaffeine, caffeine, caffeine.‚Äù  

Where is it? Ah, there it is. Close now. 

I see the throng undulating and writhing around me, an amoeba of colors and flesh penetrating the edges of my periphery. Dishes clank. Voices ‚Äî baritone and soprano ‚Äî disturb the airwaves. The blurry mass of bodies frolics everywhere, but their movement is insignificant in the scheme of things. Nothing matters until I get that beautiful pick-me-up, that sweet puckering of the soul that only comes with the ingestion of the preferred drug.  

Finally, the machine; I reach out to grasp that little cup beside it.  

‚ÄúGood morning, man.‚Äù 

Oh, gosh. Oh fuck, I think a human wants to have a conversation. Now is not the time or the place for such things. How dare this person want to talk in this citadel of public exhibition! Especially since I have not had my taste. My hit. That sweet, sweet energizer. 

The human gesticulates, concocts some words, utters them, and then stares at me. 

I am not rude, right? Now, I am terrified I am being uncivilized. I respond:

‚ÄúGood morning, friend. Sorry, sorry, just need to grab my coffee. Give me one moment.‚Äù

Sounds emanate from his mouth, but the words might as well be in Chinese. Wait, maybe they are in Chinese?

I drop these at my table, then head to the fruit section, which usually has nothing left by the time I get there, so I pick yogurt instead. Too bad it's not Greek, and even worse, it's low-fat! Just as I'm about to leave the fruit station, a Malaysian staff member approaches from my right and puts out more yellow watermelons. I'm so glad he did, so I picked some, though today for some reason, many pieces taste weird, almost like they've been left in the sun too long before arriving.‚Ä®

Anyway, my rounds are still going! this is usually the final one at the drink station. Normally, I don't drink juice, but I find a quarter glass is the sweet spot, especially when I haven't had fruit that day. Then I pour myself one cup of tea and one cup of soy milk, bring it back to the table and that's how I start my day!

Breakfast was something I didn't usually eat, but since I arrived at Network School in Forest City, things have changed. With the morning burn sessions and limited food resources, I have to nourish myself properly, or I'll probably faint in the gym!

I'm not a morning person and am almost always late for the buffet. I usually go between 9:30 and 9:45, depending on the day, and I love the rush of heading down because I know food service is nearly over by then. I've noticed that the staff remember me and even my room number now, so I guess that's a good thing.‚Ä®

I usually go straight to grab a big plate and do my rounds, carbs first (YES, this girl loves carbs!). Often, I run into fellow students doing their rounds too, so I stop for some small talk, smiling, nodding all that social stuff. Then I return to my mission: one spoon of Nasi dishes like fried rice or fried noodles, followed by a couple of pieces of chicken. I've been skipping the beef lately because it's pretty chewy, and I don't like to chew much. Then I pick my stir-fried veggies, dried shredded beef, sambal (of course!), and a couple of pieces of tempeh from that Indian curry dish I can't remember the name.‚Ä®

After that, I do my round for more protein. Normally, I avoid processed food, but some days I'll take sausages and baked beans. Oh, and they have secret ingredients in the porridge section, salted duck eggs and century eggs! I‚Äôm a sucker for those two! Then I drop my plate at a small table since all the big tables are usually full of people who arrived earlier.

I stepped into the lobby, a cavernous space, the ceiling so high that birds have taken to nesting in the rafters. Surely the industrious hotel staff would remove the birds if they could, but there was nothing they could do. The chirping of the birds, out of place in doors, joined the noise of the bustling morning crowd of hungry guests. It was a little after 9 in the morning, and several grand round tables, seating at least a dozen people, were already full of black shirted men in their mid 30s. Filling in the space at smaller tables were elderly asian families, and a smattering of honeymooning couples. 

A shy woman in hijab greeted me to take my room number. She noted it down dutifully, and welcomed me into the breakfast buffet space. A tremendous square of various buffet containers occupied the central space. As has become my routine, I made my way to the "egg corner", waiting in line among other protein inclined gentlemen for my chance to submit my omelette order. "An omelette with just peppers", I requested when it was my turn. My order submitted, I was free to pursue my other interests. Namely, whatever red meat and luke warm curry sauce could be found in the usual place, on the other side of the buffet square.

On the way to acquire the beef randang, I dodged running children and indecisive honeymooners. Passing them, my mind flashed with wonder about why one would eat rice porridge for breakfast or what one would put dried sardines on top of. Clearly many of the buffet items were catering to ideas of breakfast that I would never share.

After arriving at the silver trough containing my beef randang, I spooned the lukewarm meat and sauce on to a plate. My mind briefly wandered on the topic of how many hands had touched this spoon, and where those hands had been. In fact, where had my hands been? I pushed those thoughts from my mind and turned to find a place to rest my plate.

Of the many round tables full of people, I now had to choose who would be my companions for this breakfast. Taking stock of the situation, I found myself drawn to the quiet intense conversation happening at a table full of my fellow students, and repelled by the raucous laughter coming from a more boisterous table. This made the decision easy and I set my plate down.

"Mind if I join you guys?"

**Writing style**

And then the really important thing is **writing for skimmers.**

People today don't have the time or interest in reading really long stuff - so it's good to keep a format that:
- Is one, or max 2 sentences per paragraph.
- when possible, do bullets
- bold the stuff that you want people to truly read
- use headers
- add visuals

**On format**

I've tested many versions and I'm now at a point where I fluctuate them based on my own needs. I choose publishing over format consistency, so I can keep a sustainable cadence.

Having that said, I usually do two main ones:
- short articles (500 words or less) about something going on my life, an event I've attended, something like that
- or 3,2,1 format like the one I shared (3 brain farts, 2 smart goodies, 1 funky jam). This is nice bc it allows me to talk about many things and it's kept concise which I know people appreciate

**Visuals **

A key feedback I also always get is visuals! I do spend some time on them (30-1h) bc I think they add a lot of value and bring to life concepts that are sometimes hard to grasp - especially bc I talk mostly about very technical/futuristic things that non-technical folks may not be as familiar with. 

I use **Pinterest**, whose algorithm by now knows me pretty well and try to always use the keyword `aesthetic` after everything I search and that helps tons! Because of my particular style, I also do things like `retro aesthetic`, `vintage aesthetic`, `futuristic` etc...
